      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Why such a large difference?\n\nThis is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect**. Ethylenediamine is a bidentate ligand that forms a five-membered chelate ring with Ni²⁺, gaining a large entropic advantage over monodentate NH₃. The thermodynamic data confirm this: at I = 0.1 M the Ni–en complex has ΔS = +9.2 cal mol⁻¹ K⁻¹ versus only +1.7 cal mol⁻¹ K⁻¹ for Ni–NH₃, while the enthalpy for Ni–en is near zero (ΔH ≈ 0 kJ mol⁻¹) compared to ΔH = −15.1 kJ mol⁻¹ for Ni–NH₃. The stability gain is therefore **entropy-driven**, consistent with the release of additional solvent molecules when a single chelating ligand replaces two monodentate ones.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
